<HEADLINE>
<P>
NURSING HOME FINED $50,000 OVER VIOLATIONS ON PATIENT CARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Playa del Rey nursing home was ordered to pay $50,000 in penalties Friday for 
violations of state law regulating patient care, the Los Angeles city 
attorney's office said. 
</P>
<P>
In a Superior Court injunction, Care Enterprises West, which does business as 
the Care West Playa del Rey Nursing Center, was also ordered to take specific 
steps to avoid future violations. 
</P>
<P>
The injunction covers Lee Bangerter, a board member of Care Enterprises West, 
and Dee Bangerter, chief executive officer of the Tustin-based nursing home 
chain. 
</P>
<P>
Attorneys for Care Enterprises also pleaded no contest Friday to three criminal 
counts stemming from violations of a state Health and Safety Code section that 
regulates long-term health-care facilities. 
</P>
<P>
Most of the violations involved the failure to provide prescribed medication 
and treatment to patients, the city attorney's office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
